    <item>
      <title>The Bilattice-Valued Allegory of Relational Composition</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/the-bilattice-valued-allegory-of-relational-composition/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 14 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/the-bilattice-valued-allegory-of-relational-composition/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;hypothesis&#34;&gt;Hypothesis&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Classical Freyd-Scedrov allegories of two-valued relations (Freyd &amp;amp; Scedrov 1990) record a single channel of evidence: whether a pair &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;(x, y)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is related. The bilattice &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊗&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{2} \otimes \mathbf{2}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; of the adjoint paper separates positive evidence (told-true) from negative evidence (told-false), with independent values &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\bot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (neither) and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\top&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (both). We prove that the allegory of bilattice-valued relations on &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊗&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{2} \otimes \mathbf{2}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is a &lt;strong&gt;strictly stronger, lossless refinement&lt;/strong&gt; of the classical Freyd-Scedrov allegory, in a precise sense:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>State Change as Passage Through Contestation</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/state-change-as-passage-through-contestation/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 06 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/state-change-as-passage-through-contestation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;abstract&#34;&gt;Abstract&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href=&#34;./the-adjoint-structure-of-predication-on-bilattice-valued-fibers.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;extending operation&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\odot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; on the four-valued &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/algebra/terms/bilattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;bilattice&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\{\bot, t, f, \top\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; has an absorbing element: &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;f \odot a = f&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; for all &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (Busaniche &amp;amp; Cignoli 2014, Proposition 2). A settled denial cannot be overridden by extension alone. We show that combining &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\odot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; with the knowledge-order join &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;k&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\vee_k&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; produces a two-phase state-change mechanism: &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;k&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\vee_k&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; introduces &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\top&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (contestation) where entity and message disagree; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\odot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; resolves &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\top&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; using the message as evidence. The cycle &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;σ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∘&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Δ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\sigma \circ \Delta&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; — contestation then settlement — is sufficient to compute interactive state transitions on any system of bilattice-valued &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/subject-predicate-object.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;subject-predicate-object&lt;/a&gt; triples. We verify this on Zork I (Infocom, 1983): 250 entities, 110 rooms, 20 tested interactions, all state transitions produced by &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;k&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;/&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\vee_k / \odot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; with no rules, no conditionals, and no game-specific code. Comparison with Ceptre (Martens 2015), a linear logic programming language for interactive fiction that requires explicit rules, establishes that the &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;k&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;/&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\vee_k / \odot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; cycle achieves rule-free interactive computation on the same class of problems.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Documentation Theory: A Survey of Documents, Signs, and Records</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/documentation-theory-survey/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 03 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/documentation-theory-survey/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-question-at-the-threshold&#34;&gt;The Question at the Threshold&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;What is a document? The question seems simple until you try to answer it. A book is clearly a document. What about a photograph? A map? A museum specimen? A contract? A birth certificate? A text message? Where does documentation end and non-documentation begin?&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This is not a trivial question. How we answer it determines what we preserve, what we organize, what we make retrievable to future inquirers. It determines which traces of human activity count as evidence and which fade into loss. Documentation theory is the philosophical examination of the nature of documents, the principles governing their preservation and organization, and the relationship between documents and the knowledge they carry.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Epistemology: A Survey of Knowledge and Its Justification</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/epistemology-survey/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 03 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/epistemology-survey/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;knowledge-and-information-the-fundamental-difference&#34;&gt;Knowledge and Information: The Fundamental Difference&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Information is a difference that makes a difference — a distinction that reduces uncertainty. The phrase, originating with Gregory Bateson and later connecting to Claude Shannon&amp;rsquo;s mathematical theory, captures something essential: information is objective in the sense that it does not require interpretation. A thermostat responds to information (temperature difference) without meaning or understanding. Shannon quantified information as uncertainty reduction; Bateson emphasized that information requires a receiver capable of registering distinctions. Both insights hold.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Compute Closure on a Small Knowledge Base</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/how-to-compute-closure-on-a-small-knowledge-base/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/how-to-compute-closure-on-a-small-knowledge-base/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;You have a small knowledge base: a set of &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/subject-predicate-object.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;subject-predicate-object&lt;/a&gt; triples, each carrying an &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/epistemic-state.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;epistemic state&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\{\bot, t, f, \top\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. You want to &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/algebra/terms/closure.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;close&lt;/a&gt; it — derive everything that follows from what you have.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-starting-state&#34;&gt;The starting state&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Suppose you have five assertions:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;table&gt;&#xA;  &lt;thead&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;Triple&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;Value&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;Meaning&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/thead&gt;&#xA;  &lt;tbody&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;A extends B&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;t&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Affirmed&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;B extends C&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;t&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Affirmed&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;A extends C&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\bot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Unknown (not yet derived)&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;D extends B&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;f&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Denied&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;A extends D&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\bot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Unknown&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/tbody&gt;&#xA;&lt;/table&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-inference-rules&#34;&gt;The inference rules&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;For this example, we use one rule: &lt;strong&gt;transitivity&lt;/strong&gt;. If predicate &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is transitive and we have &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;X&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;X\ p\ Y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (value &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Z&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;Y\ p\ Z&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (value &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;), derive &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;X&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Z&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;X\ p\ Z&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; with value &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;k&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x \wedge_k y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (the knowledge-meet of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Detect Contradictions and Gaps in a Knowledge Base</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/how-to-detect-contradictions-and-gaps/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/how-to-detect-contradictions-and-gaps/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;You have a collection of assertions — a database, a set of files with frontmatter, a knowledge graph. Some assertions may contradict each other. Some information may be missing. Here is how to find both using the four &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/epistemic-state.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;epistemic states&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;assign-epistemic-states&#34;&gt;Assign epistemic states&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;For each entity-attribute pair in your data, assign one of four values:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;⊥ (unknown)&lt;/strong&gt;: the attribute is not mentioned for this entity. No source has said anything.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;t (affirmed)&lt;/strong&gt;: the attribute has a value. At least one source asserts it; no source denies it.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;f (denied)&lt;/strong&gt;: the attribute is explicitly absent or negated. A source says this entity does NOT have this attribute.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;⊤ (contested)&lt;/strong&gt;: different sources disagree. One says the attribute holds; another says it does not.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Most data systems only distinguish ⊥ (missing) and t (present). The four-valued system adds f (explicitly denied) and ⊤ (contradictory). These additional states are where the interesting information lives.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Read a Concept Lattice</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/how-to-read-a-concept-lattice/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/how-to-read-a-concept-lattice/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;You have a &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/order/terms/concept-lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;concept lattice&lt;/a&gt; — maybe drawn by software, maybe &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/order/texts/building-a-concept-lattice-by-hand.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;built by hand&lt;/a&gt;. It is a diagram of nodes connected by lines. Here is how to read it.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;each-node-is-a-concept&#34;&gt;Each node is a concept&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Every node in the lattice is a formal concept: a pair (extent, intent).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;extent&lt;/strong&gt; is the set of objects (files, entities, rows) that fall under the concept.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;intent&lt;/strong&gt; is the set of attributes (keys, column names, properties) that define it.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Extent and intent determine each other: the extent is exactly the objects that have all the attributes in the intent, and the intent is exactly the attributes shared by all the objects in the extent.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What Resource Sensitivity Means for Knowledge</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/what-resource-sensitivity-means-for-knowledge/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/what-resource-sensitivity-means-for-knowledge/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;In classical logic, knowing something is free. If you know &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, you can use &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; as many times as you want, in as many arguments as you like, and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is still there when you are done. Knowledge is unlimited and indestructible.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This is a useful fiction, but it is a fiction.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In practice, using a piece of evidence changes your relationship to it. Citing a source as support for a claim puts weight on that source. If the source turns out to be unreliable, every argument that cited it is weakened. If two sources contradict, using both does not give you twice as much knowledge — it gives you a contradiction.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Why Four Values Instead of Two?</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/why-four-values-instead-of-two/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/why-four-values-instead-of-two/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Classical logic has two values: true and false. Every proposition is one or the other. This works when you have a single, reliable source of information — a mathematical proof, a direct observation, a trusted oracle.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It breaks down when you have multiple sources that can disagree.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Suppose two databases report on whether a patient is allergic to penicillin. Database A says yes. Database B says no. What is the truth value of &amp;ldquo;the patient is allergic to penicillin&amp;rdquo;?&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>From Data Tables to Concept Lattices</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/from-data-tables-to-concept-lattices/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/from-data-tables-to-concept-lattices/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Any collection of things with named attributes is a data table. A set of YAML files with frontmatter. A spreadsheet. A database. The rows are entities, the columns are attribute names, the cells are values. This is the most common shape of structured data.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Formal concept analysis (Ganter &amp;amp; Wille 1999) takes this data table and extracts its conceptual structure. The table is a &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/logic/terms/formal-context.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;formal context&lt;/a&gt;: entities are objects, attribute names are attributes, and the cell values give the incidence relation.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Predication as Residuation</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/predication-as-residuation/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/predication-as-residuation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Predication is the act of asserting a relationship: &amp;ldquo;the file extends legibility,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;the component requires authentication,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;the document cites Shannon.&amp;rdquo; In each case, a predicate takes a subject and an object and produces an assertion. This is Frege&amp;rsquo;s insight (1879): the predicate is an unsaturated function.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Three fields independently discovered the same algebraic structure inside this act.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;lambek-grammar-is-residuation&#34;&gt;Lambek: grammar is residuation&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Lambek (1958) asked how a verb combines with its arguments to form a sentence. He proved the combination is a &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/algebra/terms/residuated-lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;residuation&lt;/a&gt;: given a product &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋅&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\cdot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that combines expressions, there are exactly two residuals:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>The Adjoint Structure of Predication on Bilattice-Valued Fibers</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/the-adjoint-structure-of-predication-on-bilattice-valued-fibers/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/the-adjoint-structure-of-predication-on-bilattice-valued-fibers/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;abstract&#34;&gt;Abstract&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;We name the mathematical object formed by a system of subject-predicate-object triples carrying values in the free bounded distributive bilattice &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊗&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{2} \otimes \mathbf{2}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; a &lt;strong&gt;predication modal geometry&lt;/strong&gt;, and prove it is a Chu space. Lambek (1958) proved that predicate-argument combination in categorial grammar is a residuation; Lawvere (1969) established a related adjunction pattern &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;∃&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊣&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∗&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊣&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;∀&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\exists \dashv f^* \dashv \forall&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in categorical logic. We instantiate residuation on &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊗&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{2} \otimes \mathbf{2}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; via the twist-product residuation of Busaniche &amp;amp; Cignoli (2014), obtaining operations &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\odot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (extending) and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⇒&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Rightarrow&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (restricting) with a verified adjunction &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;q&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a \odot p \leq_t q&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; iff &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⇒&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;q&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p \leq_t (a \Rightarrow q)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. This adjunction lifts to a fiber functor over any bilattice-valued SPO system, producing a bilattice-valued hyperdoctrine in the sense of Lawvere (1970) and Maruyama (2021). Under Jakl&amp;rsquo;s (2025) identification of the Chu construction with the twist construction — &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊗&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≅&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;C&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;u&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{2} \otimes \mathbf{2} \cong \mathrm{Chu}(\mathbf{2}, 0)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; — we prove every bilattice-valued SPO system &lt;em&gt;is&lt;/em&gt; a predication modal geometry, i.e. a predicate-indexed Chu space over &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;(\mathbf{2}, 0)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, with &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\odot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⇒&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Rightarrow&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; the Chu tensor and linear implication. The modal calculus is decidable (Rivieccio, Jung, &amp;amp; Jansana 2017); the operations and adjunction restrict to the post-closure set &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\{t, f, \top\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;; and the dynamics of iterated extension and restriction on the four-element algebra are characterized by exhaustive computation.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What Is a Formal Context?</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/what-is-a-formal-context/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/what-is-a-formal-context/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;You have a spreadsheet. Rows are things (files, people, products). Columns are attributes (author, status, type). Cells say whether a thing has an attribute, or what value it takes.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;That spreadsheet is a &lt;strong&gt;formal context&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Formal concept analysis (Ganter &amp;amp; Wille 1999) is a way to extract structure from this kind of data. The idea is simple: look at which things share which attributes, and which attributes are shared by which things.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Channel Capacity and Coding</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/channel-capacity-and-coding/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/channel-capacity-and-coding/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;assumed-audience&#34;&gt;Assumed audience&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Reading level: technical.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Background: entropy and mutual information.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Goal: understand capacity and why codes matter.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;channel-capacity&#34;&gt;Channel capacity&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A communication channel accepts an input and produces an output, but noise along the way can corrupt the signal. Channel capacity is the maximum rate at which information can pass through the channel with an error probability that can be made as small as desired. This maximum exists regardless of how clever the encoding scheme is &amp;ndash; it is a &lt;a href=&#34;../../../../humanities/domains/sociology/terms/property.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;property&lt;/a&gt; of the channel itself, determined by its noise characteristics.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Entropy and Surprise</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/entropy-and-surprise/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/entropy-and-surprise/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;assumed-audience&#34;&gt;Assumed audience&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Reading level: general adult.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Background: basic arithmetic.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Goal: understand entropy as average surprise.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;surprise&#34;&gt;Surprise&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A rare event is more surprising than a common event. Information theory quantifies this intuition: the surprise (or self-information) of an event with probability &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;−&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;log&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⁡&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;-\log_2(p)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; bits. An event with probability 1/2 carries 1 bit of surprise. An event with probability 1/8 carries 3 bits. An event that is certain (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p = 1&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) carries 0 bits &amp;ndash; no surprise at all.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Rate-Distortion and Lossy Compression</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/rate-distortion/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/rate-distortion/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;assumed-audience&#34;&gt;Assumed audience&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Reading level: technical.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Background: entropy and probability.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Goal: understand rate-distortion tradeoffs.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;core-idea&#34;&gt;Core idea&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Lossless compression has a hard floor: you cannot encode a source using fewer than &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;H&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; bits per &lt;a href=&#34;../../linguistics/topics/semiotics/terms/symbol.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;symbol&lt;/a&gt; on average without losing information. Lossy compression breaks through that floor by tolerating some distortion &amp;ndash; a controlled difference between the original data and the reconstruction. Rate-distortion theory quantifies the best possible tradeoff between compression rate and distortion, answering the question: for a given tolerance of error, what is the minimum number of bits per &lt;a href=&#34;../../linguistics/topics/semiotics/terms/symbol.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;symbol&lt;/a&gt; required?&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What is Information?</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/what-is-information/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/information/texts/what-is-information/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;assumed-audience&#34;&gt;Assumed audience&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Reading level: general adult.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Background: no math required.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Goal: understand information as a measure of uncertainty.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-core-idea&#34;&gt;The core idea&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Information is what reduces uncertainty. Before you observe an outcome, you face a set of possibilities. The observation narrows that set, and the amount of narrowing is the information gained. If you already know the outcome, the observation tells you nothing new. If the outcome surprises you, you gained information &amp;ndash; and the rarer the outcome, the more information it carries.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
